10
00:01:04,191 --> 00:01:11,161
So often it's translated as loving kindness or tender loving care, that sort of, those sorts of things.

11
00:01:11,781 --> 00:01:23,716
And they are, shall we say, the emotional relational feelings that we have, but they're not necessary in order to develop Metta.

12
00:01:24,118 --> 00:01:37,256
So love has a huge sort of spectrum from, you know, erotic to romantic to siblings to your spouse, your partner, to your boss.

13
00:01:37,837 --> 00:01:40,760
Everybody has a relationship.

14
00:01:40,781 --> 00:01:44,865
And hopefully it's one in which there's general goodwill.

15
00:01:45,186 --> 00:01:47,289
And that's really the operative word, goodwill.

16
00:01:47,790 --> 00:01:49,052
So it's to do with attitude.

17
00:01:49,632 --> 00:01:54,058
So attitude is something that sits behind the emotional life.

18
00:01:54,662 --> 00:02:00,209
And as we practice this goodwill, of course, the heart rises to it.

19
00:02:00,430 --> 00:02:01,430
That's what's supposed to happen.

20
00:02:01,712 --> 00:02:11,323
But that doesn't mean to say that when we're practicing the metta practice, if we don't feel loving, we feel depressed, anxious, et cetera, it's not working.

21
00:02:11,342 --> 00:02:12,344
It is working.

22
00:02:12,365 --> 00:02:21,475
Because every time you make an act in the mind of a determination, may you be well, may you be happy, et cetera, you're developing that attitude.

23
00:02:21,536 --> 00:02:22,576
It's as simple as that.

24
00:02:22,944 --> 00:02:51,129
um and the same of course in the opposite you see so if you keep saying to yourself i am depressed i'm so depressed uh you know may all beings be depressed then that also will bring about uh more depression so we have to be very careful what we say to ourselves so if we translate meta just as the attitude of goodwill and it manifests in three different ways uh from uh feelings of aversion we move towards love

25
00:02:51,413 --> 00:02:55,419
From feelings of selfishness, we move towards generosity.

26
00:02:56,120 --> 00:03:03,150
And from feelings of cruelty, not being nice to people, sarcasm, we move towards compassion.

27
00:03:04,592 --> 00:03:09,218
So having said that, how does it manifest in our speech?

28
00:03:09,759 --> 00:03:13,264
So here's the Buddha speaking to his monks.

29
00:03:14,466 --> 00:03:17,691
Remember, although I say monks, it's anybody who's listening, yeah?

30
00:03:18,514 --> 00:03:22,782
There are these five aspects of speech by which others may address you.

31
00:03:24,063 --> 00:03:38,385
Timely or untimely, true or false, gentle or harsh, beneficial or unbeneficial, with a mind of goodwill or of inner ill will.

32
00:03:40,128 --> 00:03:43,914
Others may address you in a timely way or an untimely way.

33
00:03:44,349 --> 00:03:48,676
They may address you in a true or what is false and then he goes through it.

34
00:03:49,377 --> 00:03:52,282
In any event, you should train yourselves.

35
00:03:52,902 --> 00:03:58,110
Our minds will remain unaffected and we will speak no evil words.

36
00:03:58,852 --> 00:04:06,503
We will remain sympathetic to the person's welfare with a mind of goodwill and with no hate.

37
00:04:07,545 --> 00:04:12,432
We will keep pervading him with awareness imbued with goodwill.

38
00:04:13,391 --> 00:04:30,415
And beginning with him, we will keep pervading the all-encompassing world with an awareness imbued with goodwill, abundant, exalted, immeasurable, free from hostility, and free from ill will.

39
00:04:30,896 --> 00:04:32,577
That's how you should train yourself.

40
00:04:33,119 --> 00:04:39,086
Now, the operative phrase for me in this is awareness imbued with goodwill.

41
00:04:39,327 --> 00:04:41,129
So it's an affectionate awareness.

42
00:04:41,750 --> 00:04:42,011
Okay?

43
00:04:42,692 --> 00:04:43,213
And...

44
00:04:43,733 --> 00:05:02,757
If you just try it, if it hasn't, if should we say it comes very rarely to you, but if you look kindly upon all people whom you meet or see, even in the street, you'll see that it's a sort of background, sort of backdrop to the way you behave.

45
00:05:03,096 --> 00:05:11,007
It has a direct effect on the way you speak and your facial expressions, eh?

46
00:05:13,129 --> 00:05:15,812
So he's very big on speech.

47
00:05:17,295 --> 00:05:18,156
Get the speech right.

48
00:05:18,596 --> 00:05:21,319
And of course, the speech comes right when the thought comes right.

49
00:05:21,379 --> 00:05:25,826
So he's always saying that the mind comes first.

50
00:05:25,886 --> 00:05:34,637
What you do with your mind, what you do with your thoughts and your imaginings, they precede everything.

51
00:05:37,000 --> 00:05:40,384
So the next thing is inaction, you see.

52
00:05:41,185 --> 00:05:42,646
So

53
00:05:43,892 --> 00:05:53,463
One acts from a position of goodwill, you are connecting with somebody, and it might be that you fall into the error of a do-gooder.

54
00:05:54,144 --> 00:05:56,125
Everybody does it at some time or other.

55
00:05:56,906 --> 00:06:06,276
And that's when we are willing to do good, we want to do good, but we're not actually listening to what the other person needs.

56
00:06:08,538 --> 00:06:13,764
And so you end up doing something, and you can't understand why they want you to leave

57
00:06:16,107 --> 00:06:17,709
Why are they not big on thank yous?

58
00:06:18,850 --> 00:06:20,411
Because you've done your best, you see.

59
00:06:21,033 --> 00:06:29,744
So you have to be careful when you want to help somebody out of goodwill that we open up.

60
00:06:30,144 --> 00:06:32,007
We ask them, what do you need?

61
00:06:32,107 --> 00:06:32,968
What do you want?

62
00:06:33,649 --> 00:06:38,014
And if, of course, you can't fulfill that need, well, you have to say, I can't do it.

63
00:06:38,887 --> 00:06:45,595
On that level, sometimes I think, definitely true for me, too quick to say yes, you know.

64
00:06:46,216 --> 00:06:55,084
So somebody says to you, a friend or a family member or somebody says, you know, I've got to do, my garden's overgrown, et cetera.

65
00:06:55,485 --> 00:06:57,867
I want to do a lot of gardening this weekend.

66
00:06:57,887 --> 00:07:03,072
You know, if you've got a spare moment, I'd really appreciate your help, you see.

67
00:07:03,413 --> 00:07:06,016
And you immediately say, oh, yeah, yeah, yeah, I'll come over Saturday.

68
00:07:06,096 --> 00:07:07,156
Yeah, I'll give you a hand, you see.

69
00:07:07,694 --> 00:07:09,737
And then when you leave, you think, why did I do that?

70
00:07:09,997 --> 00:07:14,464
I don't want to go over there doing his garden, doing the garden.

71
00:07:15,225 --> 00:07:21,576
And, of course, come Saturday morning, you've got a headache, you don't feel good, you've lost your spade and things like that.

72
00:07:22,257 --> 00:07:30,370
So it's always good, I think, when somebody asks you to do something, to just spend a moment and just say, well, give me a moment there.

73
00:07:30,411 --> 00:07:31,172
I'll think about it.

74
00:07:31,391 --> 00:07:32,593
I've got to see what I've got to do.

75
00:07:33,516 --> 00:07:35,017
Just delay a bit of time.

76
00:07:35,959 --> 00:07:49,954
Now, I trained myself, I mean, this is going back ages, to if I said yes too quickly, no matter how I felt, I would actually go and do it and go through the pain of doing something that I really didn't want to do.

77
00:07:49,994 --> 00:08:01,326
